As someone else pointed out, FMV was only optional.

And as for the Akiko: It only was there because AGA still had this
flaw of being planar. On a 386 PC you simply didn't need a
chunky to planar converter, because VGA is chunky in the first
place.

Oh and not to forget: Akiko ofcourse works from chipmem to chipmem,
so it used a hell lot of memory bandwidth at the weakest point
of the A1200: chipmem. I suppose a CPU based chunky to planar which
works from fastmem to chipmem is twice as fast (and still needs a
lot of bandwidth which you normally wouldnt want to waste).

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;      Your original question dealt with what products CBM had to sell
