One problem many of the turbo board designers didn't take serious:
A fast memory is WAY more important than fast CPU calculations for games.

If you are drawing textured polygons, 99% what you do is simply move
bytes from a texture to the framebuffer. The calculation speed does not
matter so much here.

And that's also basically the reason why all 68060 boards for the A1200
suck so bigtime. When you do plain calculations (like raytracing or
fractal stuff) the 68060 is easily faster than a Pentium 1 at the
same clock speed. But once you need to do lot's of memory accesses,
the P1 is several times faster.

But then again CBM and companies like Phase5 weren't alone with their
&quot;we need fast cpu, we dont care for memory speed&quot; philosophy. For
example, the Archimedes also suffered heavily from this problem of
having a fast CPU but not being able to do anything with it due to
slow memory.
